WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.360
So, I want to share with you a story of evolution, and as you can see, this evolution unsurprisingly

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:14.840
starts at sea.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:21.040
See, this is me, and I just started out my master's degree in marine ecology, and I went

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:27.360
out to the Red Sea to do some fish sampling, and when I was there, I was completely overwhelmed

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:31.680
by the beauty of the coral reef, with all these beautiful shapes, colors, and really

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:33.480
nice-looking fish.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:37.720
But when I was done sampling and looking at all these crazy fish, and it was time for

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:44.320
me to go in and fill in the data, I was welcomed by this, ugly, unintuitive, hard-to-navigate

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:52.000
Microsoft Access forms, and this is the starting point for our journey.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.840
This journey is a walk-through of how I moved from using Microsoft Access to using Google

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:05.680
Sheets and using R to do our own lab custom-made database.

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:11.519
And I hope that whether you're using Microsoft Access now or Google Sheets or any of these

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:17.440
different alternatives for making data forms, you will find some lessons that I've learned,

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:21.279
something that you could use in your workflow.

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:25.559
So the first step in this walk-through was to understand our needs.

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:30.400
And to understand our needs, I just have to say a few words about how exactly we operate.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:36.800
So we are, as I said, a marine ecology lab, and we are going, using scuba diving to do

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:38.639
some underwater surveys.

00:01:38.639 --> 00:01:45.839
So we go out there, as you can see here, with water-resistant piece of paper and a pencil,

00:01:45.839 --> 00:01:51.519
and we just do some records of the fish species, and they're abundant when we are underwater.

00:01:51.519 --> 00:01:56.080
So why do we need Microsoft, why did we need Microsoft Access to do that?

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:58.919
So first, we know we needed a big data set.

00:01:58.919 --> 00:02:03.239
So as you can see from this photo, these are taken several years apart.

00:02:03.239 --> 00:02:05.480
We are doing this for a long time.

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:08.240
And we have no intention of stopping any time soon.

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:10.639
And you can see why.

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:17.360
Another thing, we need a strict, for our database, we need a strict form of data validation.

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:23.479
Because this fellow, their name is Pomacantus Imperator, and if you don't write that exactly

00:02:23.479 --> 00:02:27.160
as the bottom row, you're going to have a lot of problems down the road.

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:32.919
And that's true for any of the cells that we have in our data form.

00:02:32.919 --> 00:02:36.360
Most importantly, we need relational data.

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:42.039
So our data is structured in a relational format, where we have the trip, the topmost

00:02:42.039 --> 00:02:48.119
level is mainly the location where we are diving in the world, and the date.

00:02:48.119 --> 00:02:54.399
Then we have the site, which is, like, more close-up of who is diving where exactly, like,

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:56.839
in the actual dive site.

00:02:56.839 --> 00:03:01.020
Then we have the transect, the underwater environmental data.

00:03:01.020 --> 00:03:04.199
So that's the visibility, the depth, the substrate.

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:07.080
Lastly, we have the observation itself.

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:12.240
The species of the fish and its abundance.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:16.440
When we used Microsoft Access, unknowingly, we made some sacrifices.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:19.600
So first, we had really bad user interface.

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:23.800
So for us, it was really hard to work with Microsoft Access.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:28.600
I remember clicking the wrong button a few times, getting this really loud error message.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:29.600
It was a hell to work.

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:32.800
At least for me, it was a hell to work.

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:36.520
The last thing that was really detrimental to our workflow is that we couldn't figure

00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:41.039
out how to do simultaneous data entry for our needs.

00:03:41.039 --> 00:03:42.179
Sorry.

00:03:42.179 --> 00:03:48.960
So what happened is we had to actually e-mail the database file from one person to another,

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:51.360
and so we took turns filling in the data.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:56.600
So sometimes it could take more than a week until it was your turn to do so, and it was

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:00.360
really detrimental to the quality of the data.

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:07.360
Lastly, since we didn't build the database ourselves, it was really hard for us to make

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:11.000
any customization needed for our needs.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.639
So for example, we are working on both the Mediterranean Sea and the Red Sea.

00:04:15.639 --> 00:04:19.079
There are completely different seas with completely different animals.

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:23.339
We need different protocols, and for this, we need a different database.

00:04:23.339 --> 00:04:26.279
So that was also a problem.

00:04:26.279 --> 00:04:32.600
Taking into account all of these things, we set out to create our own database.

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:34.679
So what we did was we create.

00:04:34.679 --> 00:04:36.559
So that was our prototype now, okay?

00:04:36.559 --> 00:04:44.399
We have this giant Google spreadsheet for an entire expedition, and every day, we had

00:04:44.399 --> 00:04:51.920
someone in charge of manually creating different spreadsheets within the spreadsheet, different

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:56.760
worksheets for each of the different surveyors of that day.

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:02.519
So when I created this Google Sheet prototype, I needed to take some drastic measures so

00:05:02.519 --> 00:05:06.160
I won't have any user error, and I didn't know how to do that.

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:13.880
So my first idea was to have this really horrendous color coding, and I'm going to show you.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:16.640
We had this bright red trip data.

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:17.920
So these are different forms.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:19.760
All the forms are in different colors.

00:05:19.760 --> 00:05:26.519
So we have this trip data in red, then we had this yellow, is it yellow here?

00:05:26.519 --> 00:05:34.480
This yellow site data, the green transect data, and lastly, that blue observer data.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:41.040
So as you can see, really nice colors, and to connect this, to connect all of these,

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:48.160
the observers themselves had to copy and paste IDs so we could create this relational data.

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:54.119
So what happens is that for every expedition, we have this, a lot of different worksheets

00:05:54.119 --> 00:05:56.119
within a spreadsheet.

00:05:56.119 --> 00:06:02.559
As you can see, some red, some blue, it's a whole mess, but this is where we used Google

00:06:02.559 --> 00:06:03.559
Sheets.

00:06:03.559 --> 00:06:07.279
It was Google Sheets at the time, now it's Google Sheets 4.

00:06:07.279 --> 00:06:14.359
We could read by that color coding, and then using that ID that the users had to copy and

00:06:14.359 --> 00:06:21.320
paste, we could use dplyr to connect it all to a flat data set that we can work with.

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:27.359
Now I know it's a mess, and if you have this expression right now, yeah, this is the expression

00:06:27.359 --> 00:06:31.440
that all my colleagues had when I presented that idea, and I told them, let's stick with

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:37.600
it, it can be worse than what we currently have.

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:38.679
It wasn't worse.

00:06:38.679 --> 00:06:41.880
But the thing is, it doesn't have to be perfect, all right?

00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:45.119
So this is us.

00:06:45.119 --> 00:06:50.519
This is Crete 2019, and I know it doesn't look like that, but we are currently hard

00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:55.519
at work filling in the data.

00:06:55.519 --> 00:06:58.559
So as you can see, we're doing that together.

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:00.279
So that's an important thing.

00:07:00.279 --> 00:07:04.799
We managed to solve one big problem, which was the simultaneous data entry.

00:07:04.799 --> 00:07:08.119
So now that we can work online, as you can see, it's the blue one.

00:07:08.119 --> 00:07:14.239
So once we managed to solve this problem, and I know that the prototype works, it's

00:07:14.239 --> 00:07:21.640
time for us to adjust, to make the necessary adjustments to make this data form, database,

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:23.559
much better to work with.

00:07:23.559 --> 00:07:26.239
So how did we do that?

00:07:26.239 --> 00:07:30.799
Mainly by increasing our dependency of Google Drive and Google Sheets 4 package.

00:07:30.799 --> 00:07:36.760
So we have a great tool for actually working with Google Drive and Google Sheets, and we

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:40.059
managed to automate the entire process.

00:07:40.059 --> 00:07:48.040
So what we did at first, we had an offline file that replaced the old yellow and red

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:49.600
worksheets that we had.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:51.359
Now they're offline.

00:07:51.359 --> 00:07:57.239
And from this, we can set out to automate the whole thing.

00:07:57.239 --> 00:08:02.880
And we used Google Drive for the housekeeping and navigation, and for the manipulation,

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:05.320
we used Google Sheets 4.

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:12.359
More specifically, we had Drive MacDir to create individual folders for every sampling

00:08:12.359 --> 00:08:13.359
day.

00:08:13.359 --> 00:08:19.279
So now instead of having one big Google spreadsheets that's just somewhere on Drive, we have this

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:27.200
hierarchy when we have an expedition directory, and within it for each day, we have a different

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:28.440
folder.

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:32.840
So it's much more organized.

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:38.640
For Sheets 4 Create, the function we used to upload that offline file from which we

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:45.919
create the metadata, we used Drive Find and Drive CP in order to copy and paste preexisting

00:08:45.919 --> 00:08:50.760
templates that we had to today's folder.

00:08:50.760 --> 00:09:02.200
So then we used Sheet Copy and Range Write in order to manipulate those preexisting templates,

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:07.960
and to manipulate these preexisting templates into whatever necessary for today.

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:11.719
So change in site numbers, hour, et cetera.

00:09:11.719 --> 00:09:17.359
Lastly, what I really like is that we have Drive Share, and we use this function in order

00:09:17.359 --> 00:09:23.539
to send out specific e-mail for specific users so they can only change their own data.

00:09:23.539 --> 00:09:26.400
So they can only fill out their own form.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:30.719
And it's really good because they don't have to mess around with anything in the database.

00:09:30.719 --> 00:09:36.000
And they can't accidentally erase or change someone else's data.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.559
And for them, it's really easy because all they have to do now is get an e-mail, and

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:44.080
they sit out and they fill out the forms.

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:46.359
So this is what we get.

00:09:46.359 --> 00:09:51.479
This is a folder for a day, and we have the metadata up there, and as you can see, we

00:09:51.479 --> 00:09:56.640
have individual spreadsheets for each of the different observers.

00:09:56.719 --> 00:10:05.440
In order to do that, I had to do some, to be creative in a way, and let's zoom in into

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:06.440
one of the spreadsheets.

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:09.559
So first thing, as you can see, the colors are much better.

00:10:09.559 --> 00:10:12.840
They're not really bright anymore.

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:21.880
And I wanted to have a strong connection between the environmental data and the fish data.

00:10:21.880 --> 00:10:26.479
So we're doing ecology, which is basically the relationship between a species and its

00:10:26.479 --> 00:10:27.479
environment.

00:10:27.479 --> 00:10:31.799
So we wanted to have this demonstrated in our database, in our forms.

00:10:31.799 --> 00:10:39.479
To do that, you can see columns A and B don't follow the same logic as columns C and H.

00:10:39.479 --> 00:10:44.080
Some people would say it's unorthodox, incorrect.

00:10:44.080 --> 00:10:50.960
For those of you who can't see that, A and B, each row does not represent an observation.

00:10:51.039 --> 00:10:53.239
It's a long format.

00:10:53.239 --> 00:10:58.880
But once you realize that you can go from this long format into a wide format fairly

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:05.320
easily using tidyverse, then it opens up a whole world of possibilities for you.

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:14.000
For example, on another project where we do quadrat sampling, I managed to take the exact

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:23.159
piece of paper that surveyors go to, to the field, and I managed to copy it almost verbatim

00:11:23.159 --> 00:11:29.280
into a digital form, making the transition from the actual survey data, from the actual

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:36.000
real-world data to the digital data much more intuitive for my users.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:43.799
And I encourage you all to think about how user-oriented your data forms are at the

00:11:43.799 --> 00:11:45.159
moment.

00:11:45.159 --> 00:11:48.919
Because I know I've been taught as well that you should make your data as computer-readable

00:11:48.919 --> 00:11:53.400
as possible for analysis, visualization, et cetera.

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:59.919
But at the same time, all of us were taught how easy it is to manipulate the data shape.

00:11:59.919 --> 00:12:07.719
So we could all stand to benefit from having more user-oriented data so we could then get

00:12:07.719 --> 00:12:12.000
so we could minimize the errors from those users, because it would be much more intuitive

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:20.599
for them to fill in the data forms and have we make our data much better at the end.

00:12:20.599 --> 00:12:22.400
So this was our project.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:24.719
This is how it went for quite a while.

00:12:24.719 --> 00:12:26.520
This worked quite well.

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:33.080
It was really automated, and we worked for two years or so on this type of forms.

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:39.559
But as we continued to use this, we realized that we needed to make additional changes,

00:12:39.559 --> 00:12:46.880
because as we kept using this database, so did our needs change.

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:53.200
So we realized that having an offline file was creating a bottleneck, because we needed

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:59.200
to have someone who knows exactly how to type in the specific observer's name and

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:01.080
all kinds of stuff.

00:13:01.080 --> 00:13:05.239
Then we decided to put that on the cloud as well.

00:13:05.239 --> 00:13:12.080
And then using the Google Sheets GS4 browse function, we can open up the browser directly

00:13:12.080 --> 00:13:18.799
from RStudio, and then it opened up something like that, sorry.

00:13:18.799 --> 00:13:24.000
And then you just fill in with data validation, you fill in who are the observers for today.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:30.599
So as you can see, I took this opportunity to thank all my colleagues here, my collaborators,

00:13:30.599 --> 00:13:33.479
whose feedback was really what drove this thing forward.

00:13:33.479 --> 00:13:38.320
So while I did the coding and I presented the idea and everything, their feedback is

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:39.700
what drove this thing forward.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:44.940
If it wasn't for them, we would still be stuck in that ugly call off phase, honestly.

00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:47.840
So thanks for that.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:52.559
Another thing, since we built this thing from the ground up, now it's really easy for

00:13:52.559 --> 00:13:55.840
us to make adjustments whenever we need.

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:58.900
So for example, let's say we have another project now.

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:03.159
We just have a template, change a few lines of code, not even change, we just add a few

00:14:03.159 --> 00:14:08.320
lines of code, and we now have a whole new database for another project, really easy

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:10.219
to work with.

00:14:10.219 --> 00:14:16.479
So basically we can do whatever we want using Google Sheets 4 and RStudio.

00:14:16.479 --> 00:14:22.679
And now it's even more automated in a sense that you just run one line of code.

00:14:22.679 --> 00:14:30.760
For example, you select what kind of projects are you working on, fill in the data, like

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:38.479
the actual observer data, and just here, as you can see here also, you just confirm that

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:42.440
it's correct, and then R does anything for you, everything for you.

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:49.380
You can take a few minutes, make some coffee, and then you spend the afternoon filling data

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:51.979
with your friends together and colleagues.

00:14:51.979 --> 00:14:55.159
So this is us enjoying filling data.

00:14:55.159 --> 00:14:57.880
As you can see, we really like our job.

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:05.320
I hope this convinced you on the power of using R right from the start of the data manipulation

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:06.320
stage.

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:10.880
I mean, right from actually getting the data.

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:18.640
If you want to explore this option of having a more custom-made database, some things to

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:20.020
consider.

00:15:20.020 --> 00:15:25.679
So the first thing, consider what exactly do you need out of your database.

00:15:25.679 --> 00:15:31.159
Think about whether you are currently meeting your needs or are you simply overkilling your

00:15:31.159 --> 00:15:34.159
needs with what you are doing right now.

00:15:34.159 --> 00:15:37.919
And in order to meet those needs, don't be afraid to be creative.

00:15:37.919 --> 00:15:43.919
If you need a triangular-shaped pyramid data, you can do it, okay?

00:15:43.919 --> 00:15:47.919
Don't be afraid to pursue the type of data that you want.

00:15:47.919 --> 00:15:54.599
Lastly, pay attention to whatever your user's feedback is and make sure to keep moving forward

00:15:54.599 --> 00:15:57.760
with whatever project you are currently working on.

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:01.280
And if you want to see how we keep moving this project forward or you're interested

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:07.479
in the code, try to replicate this for your own needs, then you can go to our GitHub page

00:16:07.479 --> 00:16:11.080
and I'll make sure to upload this slide as well to GitHub.

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:15.559
And if you have any questions, I'm free, I'm willing to help.

00:16:15.559 --> 00:16:16.559
And thank you for listening.

00:16:16.559 --> 00:16:17.559
Thank you.

00:16:17.559 --> 00:16:17.559


